  82. <p><b>Wotsits</b> is a brand of <a href="/wiki/Cheese_puffs" title="Cheese puffs">cheesy flavour corn puffs</a> sold by <a href="/wiki/Walkers_(snack_foods)" title="Walkers (snack foods)">Walkers</a>. The most common form are cheese flavoured curly shapes. However, over the years, various other shapes (such as waffle-shaped Wotsits) and flavours (such as <a href="/wiki/Prawn_cocktail" title="Prawn cocktail">prawn cocktail</a> and flaming hot) have also been sold. "Limited edition" Wotsits have also appeared on more than one occasion.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2007)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>The brand was stretched into Whopping Wotsits, Weenie Wotsits, Waffle Wotsits as well as frozen Wotsits. All came into the market under <a href="/wiki/Golden_Wonder" title="Golden Wonder">Golden Wonder</a>'s ownership managed by Sir Nigel Parrott between the years 1993 and 2002. The brand name occurs in the singular, "Wotsit", referring to an individual corn puff. It is an allusion to the slang term "whatsit", to which it is phonetically identical. Wotsits packaging often come with a joke or trivia section on the back. The brand was the first to introduce inserts into its packs in 1994, with the insertion of "<a href="/wiki/Pogs" title="Pogs">Pogs</a>". It also inserted merlin football stickers and other inserts aimed at 11-year-old boys. The brand was advertised with the strapline "you only get a whoosh with a Wotsit" between 1994 and 2002 following a campaign designed by JWT of a play on words.</p>↩
  83. <p>The brand was previously owned by Golden Wonder, but was sold off separately to Walkers when Golden Wonder changed hands in 2002.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Prior to this, Walkers sold the similar American product <a href="/wiki/Cheetos" title="Cheetos">Cheetos</a>, which was considered a rival in the UK market.</p>↩
  84. <p>In 2003, the advertising agency <a href="/wiki/Abbott_Mead_Vickers" title="Abbott Mead Vickers" class="mw-redirect">Abbott Mead Vickers</a> made a public apology when the Parliamentary Select Committee on Health brought to light a private brief that it had made to <a href="/wiki/Frito-Lay" title="Frito-Lay">Frito-Lay</a> (Walkers' owners) where it proposed encouraging children (4 to 9 years old) to believe that "<i>Wotsits are for me — I'm going to buy them when I get the chance and <a href="/wiki/Pester_power" title="Pester power">pester Mum</a> for them when she next goes shopping</i>".<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>↩
  85. <p>Another variety of Wotsits were "Mealtime Potato Shapes", made from potato and cheese and meant to be baked in the oven.<sup id="cite_ref-catsearch_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-catsearch-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> They were launched in 2000, but were discontinued.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2007)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>↩
  86. <p>In February 2007, Wotsits were re-launched as the way they were being cooked changed. Instead of frying Wotsits, they started baking them. They were put into new packaging (along with other Walkers brands such as <a href="/wiki/Quavers" title="Quavers">Quavers</a> and <a href="/wiki/Monster_Munch" title="Monster Munch">Monster Munch</a>) to coincide with the fact they were being baked and in 2009, Wotsits, Quavers, Squares and French Fries changed packaging again to show that Wotsits now have 95 calories in multipack bags and 99 calories in standard bags.</p>↩
  87. <p>Wotsits were the sponsor of <a href="/wiki/SMTV_Live" title="SMTV Live">SMTV Live</a> from 4 January 2003 until the show's discontinuation on 27 December 2003.</p>↩
  88. <p>Wotsits are featured as the main course of the officers' dinner in the British SciFi sitcom, Hyperdrive, Season 1 Episode 3.</p>↩
  89. <p>A Limited Edition Product Called "Wotsits Zombie Fingers" was sold for halloween 2013 and 2014 which come in the Flamin Hot flavour.</p>↩
